==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|ang}} {{term|æcer|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|akraz|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|h₂éǵros|lang=ang|field}}.  Compare Latin {{term|ager}}, Ancient Greek {{term|ἀγρός|sc=polytonic}}.

===Pronunciation===
*{{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈeɪkə/}}
* {{audio|en-us-acre.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*: {{rhymes|eɪkə(r)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{obsolete}} A [[field]].
# A unit of surface area (''symbol'' a. ''or'' ac.), originally as much as a yoke of oxen could plough in a day; later defined as an area 1 [[chain]] (22 yd) by 1 [[furlong]] (220 yd), or 4,840 [[square yard]]s.  Equivalent to about 4,046.86 square metres.
# {{in plural|informal}} A large amount (of area).
#: ''I like my new house - there’s '''acres''' of space!''

